		<h2 class="ai-h2">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
	</div>
	<div class="ai-faq">
		<details class="ai-faq-item">
			<summary class="ai-faq-q">
				<span class="ai-faq-q-text">Can AI-generated textile designs be copyrighted?</span>
				<svg class="ai-faq-icon" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="14" height="14">
					<path d="M 4 6 L 8 10 L 12 6" fill="none" stroke="#605dba" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
			</summary>
			<p class="ai-faq-a">The copyright status of AI-generated designs depends on the tool's training data and the
				degree of human creative input. In the United States, the Copyright Office has ruled that works created
				entirely by AI without human creative contribution are not eligible for copyright protection. However,
				designs where a human artist provides significant creative direction — such as composing detailed
				prompts, selecting and arranging AI outputs, and making manual modifications — may qualify for copyright
				on the human-authored elements. Adobe Firefly offers the strongest commercial copyright protection
				because its training data is limited to licensed Adobe Stock content and public-domain works where
				rights have been cleared. Midjourney and DALL-E have more uncertain copyright status for commercial
				textile use because their training data includes web-scraped images. For mills producing designs for
				brand customers, the safest approach is to use AI as a concept generation tool and have a human designer
				create the final production artwork, or to use tools like Firefly and Pattern Bank that offer copyright
				indemnification for commercial use.</p>
		</details>
		<details class="ai-faq-item">
			<summary class="ai-faq-q">
				<span class="ai-faq-q-text">How does AI handle pattern repeat generation for textile printing?</span>
				<svg class="ai-faq-icon" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="14" height="14">
					<path d="M 4 6 L 8 10 L 12 6" fill="none" stroke="#605dba" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
			</summary>
			<p class="ai-faq-a">AI-powered pattern repeat generation automates the most time-consuming manual task in
				textile design — creating seamless repeating patterns that match at all four edges with no visible
				seams. Pattern Bank and similar tools use convolutional neural networks trained on thousands of textile
				repeats to analyze a base design and compute optimal repeat boundaries. The AI identifies the dominant
				motif elements, calculates the repeat dimensions that best preserve the design intent, and blends edge
				regions using content-aware fill algorithms. Advanced tools offer multiple repeat types: block repeat
				(simple grid), half-drop repeat (offset every other row), brick repeat (offset every other column), and
				random or scattered repeats for organic patterns. The AI also handles complex technical requirements for
				textile printing, including rapport size specifications for rotary screens, overlap allowances for
				wallpaper-style matching, and color separation boundaries that ensure each screen layer has adequate
				registration tolerance. iFactory's Pattern AI module generates production-ready repeat files that are
				compatible with all major textile CAD and RIP systems.</p>
		</details>
		<details class="ai-faq-item">
			<summary class="ai-faq-q">
				<span class="ai-faq-q-text">What skills do textile designers need to work effectively with AI
					tools?</span>
				<svg class="ai-faq-icon" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="14" height="14">
					<path d="M 4 6 L 8 10 L 12 6" fill="none" stroke="#605dba" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
			</summary>
			<p class="ai-faq-a">Textile designers working with AI tools need three skill sets beyond traditional design
				expertise. Prompt engineering is the most immediately useful skill — the ability to write structured,
				detailed prompts that consistently produce usable designs requires practice and an understanding of how
				different AI models interpret language. Designers who document successful prompts and build prompt
				libraries achieve 3 to 5 times higher productivity than those who write prompts from scratch each time.
				Color management knowledge is essential because AI-generated colors rarely match production-ready
				specifications — designers must understand color separation, Pantone mapping, and how different printing
				technologies (screen, digital, rotary) handle color. Technical textile knowledge — understanding how
				repeat size, motif scale, and color count affect production cost and feasibility — becomes more
				important rather than less important in an AI-augmented workflow, because AI can rapidly generate
				designs that are technically impossible to produce. iFactory's AI Design module includes role-specific
				training that helps designers build these skills incrementally, with guided prompt templates and
				automated production-feasibility checking that flags non-producible designs before they reach the
				sampling stage.</p>
		</details>
		<details class="ai-faq-item">
			<summary class="ai-faq-q">
				<span class="ai-faq-q-text">How does AI color reduction affect print quality compared to manual color
					separation?</span>
				<svg class="ai-faq-icon" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="14" height="14">
					<path d="M 4 6 L 8 10 L 12 6" fill="none" stroke="#605dba" stroke-width="2.2" stroke-linecap="round"
						stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
				</svg>
			</summary>
			<p class="ai-faq-a">AI color reduction has reached parity with manual color separation for the majority of
				commercial textile applications and exceeds manual quality in certain areas. For designs with 8 to 14
				target colors — the most common range for rotary screen printing — modern AI quantization algorithms
				produce color separations that experienced print technicians rate as equal or superior to manual
				separations in blind tests, particularly for complex designs with photographic elements, gradients, and
				fine detail. The CIEDE2000 perceptual color difference formula used by advanced AI tools produces color
				mappings that better preserve visual contrast and detail than the nearest-color and manual selection
				methods traditionally used by screen printers. For very low color counts (2 to 5 colors), experienced
				human color separators still hold an advantage in preserving design intent through selective color
				merging, though the gap is narrowing with each generation of AI tools. For high-color digital printing
				(full CMYK plus spot colors), AI color management outperforms manual methods by automatically generating
				ICC profiles optimized for specific fabric and ink combinations.</p>
		</details>
		<details class="ai-faq-item">
			<summary class="ai-faq-q">
				<span class="ai-faq-q-text">What is the ROI of implementing AI in a textile mill design
